issue.title: PushNotifications not working on Android 13
issue.body:
# Preliminary Info

### What Airship dependencies are you using?
"@ua/react-native-airship": "15.2.4",
"react": "18.2.0",
"react-native": "0.70.8",
"@react-native-firebase/analytics": "14.2.2",
"@react-native-firebase/app": "14.2.2",
"@react-native-firebase/crashlytics": "14.2.2",
"@react-native-firebase/messaging": "14.2.2",
    
Also tried to use the latest: 17.4.3

### What are the versions of any relevant development tools you are using?
buildToolsVersion = "31.0.0"
minSdkVersion = 29
compileSdkVersion = 31
targetSdkVersion = 31
supportLibVersion = "29.0.0"



# Report

### What unexpected behavior are you seeing?
I have the latest UA configured for Android and iOS
Both with the complete data configured all good.

I get the channelIDS I get that the notifications are activated in both.
But when I send any type of notification, either push notification or literally messages from the portal

iOS display the listener:
```
    Airship.addListener(EventType.PushReceived, (event) => {
      console.log('PushReceived:', JSON.stringify(event));
    });
```

But android never ever trigger that message.
I have tried to do release mode, dev mode... all modes I could possible try I tried on different Android 13 Devices.
I get no response at all.

Here is my configuration inside the app:
```
    Airship.takeOff({
      default: {
        appSecret: appSecret,
        appKey: appKey
      },
      site: 'us', // use "eu" for EU cloud projects
      urlAllowList: ['*'],
      urlAllowListScopeOpenUrl: ['*'],
      inProduction: true
    });

    Airship.push.setUserNotificationsEnabled(true);

    return Airship.push.isUserNotificationsEnabled().then(() => {
      return Airship.push.enableUserNotifications();
    });
```

Did I miss any type of configuration? I have followed the example given in the project.

I also tried to compile the project with version 33 and target as 33.
That enables push notification request from the app, that 31 doesn't. But still no go with any push notification information.

comment.body:
I am trying to configure airship following way. Please tell me if i'm missing something. It is to be noted that I have same setup and notifications in my iOS device are working fine. In case of android, Channel Id also gets registered which I can see on Airship dashboard. 
Interestingly when I send push notification, my notification is received in messaging().setBackgroundMessageHandler() but doesn't appear on screen.

Following steps are used to configure airship in my react native app.

1. On app launch I initialise airship by calling takeOff method in App.tsx
 UrbanAirship.takeOff({
        default: {
            appSecret: env.AIRSHIP_APP_SECRET_LIVE,
            appKey: env.AIRSHIP_APP_KEY_LIVE
        },
        site: "us",
        urlAllowList: ["*"],
        android: {
          notificationConfig: {
              icon: "ic_notification",
              accentColor: "#00ff00",
          }
      }
      })

2. Once user logs in UrbanAirship.setUserNotificationsEnabled(true) is called.

3. For android, I also added xml folder in android/app/src/main. ua_custom_notification_channels.xml was placed inside xml folder.
Its content is given below.
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<resources>
    <NotificationChannel
        id="com.cch.intellify"
        name="IntelliShift"
        description="Notification channel"
        importance="3" />
</resources>

Whenever i set the priority, the file in android/app/build/intermediates/merged_manifests/debug/AndroidManifest.xml gets overwritten upon building the app. 
Currently in my project "io.invertase.firebase.messaging.ReactNativeFirebaseMessagingHeadlessService" and "com.wix.reactnativenotifications.fcm.FcmInstanceIdListenerService" have no priority set (0 by default), "com.google.firebase.messaging.FirebaseMessagingService" has priority = -500 and "com.urbanairship.push.fcm.AirshipFirebaseMessagingService" has priority = -1. 
I tried to change urbanship's priority to 100 but it reverted back to -1

comment.body: @zuhasohail18 its perfectly normal to have at least two firebase messaging service. Firebase dependency comes with one which Airship depends on. What matters is which service is higher priority.  You should see it in the manifest for those services: `<intent-filter android:priority="100">` if its not set on the intent-filter then it defaults to 0. Highest priority service will receive all the messages.

comment.body:
@rlepinski I have two push providers right now. Following are there details.
        <service
            android:name="com.google.firebase.messaging.FirebaseMessagingService"
            android:directBootAware="true"
            android:exported="false" >
            <intent-filter android:priority="-500" >
                <action android:name="com.google.firebase.MESSAGING_EVENT" />
            </intent-filter>
        </service>

        <service
            android:name="com.urbanairship.push.fcm.AirshipFirebaseMessagingService"
            android:exported="false" >
            <intent-filter android:priority="-1" >
                <action android:name="com.google.firebase.MESSAGING_EVENT" />
            </intent-filter>
        </service>

I never added the "com.google.firebase.messaging.FirebaseMessagingService" in app. It just got added by default when I integrated urbanairship. Now I'm unable to receive notifications on android. I tried removing provider but that file in merged_manifests gets overwritten everytime I build the project. 
@berseck Could you please help me understand how you removed that provider.
